  <div class="lesson-content-body col-xs-12 ">

        <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-6">
            In different units, the speed of light in a vacuum is:
            <ul>
                <li><span class="lesson-content-speedlight">3 x 10<sup>8</sup> m/s</span></li>
                <li><span class="lesson-content-speedlight">300,000,000 m/s</span></li>
                <li><span class="lesson-content-speedlight">300,000 km/s</span> </li>
            </ul>

            A high velocity bullet leaves the gun at a speed of approximately 1 km/s, 
            therefore light is 300 thousand times faster than a speeding bullet.

            <h3>The Quantity c<sup>2</sup></h3>
            c<sup>2</sup> is the speed of light squared.
            <br/>
            c<sup>2</sup> = c x c
            <br/>
            c<sup>2</sup> = (3 x 10<sup>8</sup>)  x (3 x 10<sup>8</sup>) = 9 x 10<sup>16</sup>  (m/s)<sup>2</sup>
            <br/><br/>
            E = m c<sup>2</sup> = m x (9 x 10<sup>16</sup>)
            
            <h3>Precise Value</h3>
            By definition, the precise value is:
            <span class="lesson-content-speedlight">299,792,458 m/s</span>
        </div>

